  "prompt": "Is a heart attack a painful death?",
  "response": "A heart attack, or myocardial infarction, can be painful but does not always result in death. The experience of pain during a heart attack varies from person to person. Some individuals describe it as intense chest pain or pressure, often radiating to the arm, neck, jaw, or back. Others may experience milder symptoms or none at all, known as a \"silent\" heart attack.\n\nIf a heart attack is severe and leads to death, the level of pain in the final moments can depend on the individual's condition, the extent of damage to the heart, and whether medical intervention is available. In some cases, pain may be managed with medications like nitroglycerin or opioids, but in others, the event can be sudden and distressing.\n\nIt's important to recognize the symptoms of a heart attack (e.g., chest discomfort, shortness of breath, nausea, lightheadedness) and seek immediate medical attention to improve outcomes.",
